update public.lessons l set enhancements = $ench${"industryStory":"A retailer pushed a \"small\" checkout change live on a Friday with no testing. Over the weekend every order with a discount code charged the full price. By Monday they had hundreds of angry customers and a day of refunds and apologies.\n\nThe change worked on the developer's machine. What was missing was someone asking \"what could go wrong here, and how do we check it before customers do?\" That question is software testing.","visualAid":{"type":"comparison","title":"QA vs QC vs Testing","headers":["Term","Focus","Example"],"rows":[["QA (Quality Assurance)","Process — preventing defects","Improving how stories are refined"],["QC (Quality Control)","Product — finding defects","Reviewing and inspecting the build"],["Testing","The activity of checking","Running test cases against the app"]],"caption":"People use these interchangeably, but knowing the difference signals professionalism."},"badGood":{"label":"answering \"what is testing?\" in an interview","bad":"\"Testing is when you click around the app to see if it works.\"","good":"\"Testing is the process of evaluating software against expectations to find defects and provide information about quality, so the business can make informed release decisions.\""},"davidTip":"Early in your career it is tempting to define testing as \"finding bugs\". In real QA teams, the testers who get promoted talk about testing as *providing information about risk*. Finding bugs is part of it — but your real product is confidence (or a clear warning) for the people deciding whether to ship.","miniChallenge":"Pick any app on your phone. Write down five things a tester should check before a new version is released — and for each, one way it could fail a real user.","modelAnswer":"## Example (a food delivery app)\n- Place an order — payment could be taken twice\n- Apply a promo code — discount could not be applied\n- Track delivery — map could show the wrong location\n- Cancel an order — refund could fail\n- Log in — could lock out a valid user after one wrong attempt\n\nEach one ties a check to a real user impact — that is testing thinking, not just clicking.","portfolioBuilder":"Start a \"QA Glossary\" note today. Add your own one-line definitions of testing, QA and QC. By the end of the course this becomes a credible artefact you can talk through in interviews.","resourcePreview":{"name":"Software Testing Glossary","purpose":"Plain-English definitions of the core testing terms used throughout the course.","whenToUse":"Keep it open while you learn; revise from it before interviews.","formats":["PDF","DOCX"]}}$ench$::jsonb
from public.modules m join public.courses c on c.id = m.course_id
where l.module_id = m.id and c.slug = '90-day-software-testing-career-roadmap'
  and m.module_number = 1 and l.lesson_number = 1;

update public.lessons l set enhancements = $ench${"industryStory":"A fintech skipped a regression check to hit a deadline. A change to the login flow quietly broke password reset. Support was flooded, the fix took three days, and the \"saved\" time cost far more than it would have to test.\n\nCompanies do not test because it is nice to have — they test because untested software is a business risk.","visualAid":{"type":"timeline","title":"The cost of a bug grows the later it is found","steps":[{"label":"Requirements","detail":"Cheapest to fix — just reword a sentence"},{"label":"Development","detail":"Costs more — code must change"},{"label":"Testing","detail":"More again — re-code and re-test"},{"label":"Production","detail":"Most expensive — customers hit it; reputation, refunds, hotfixes"}],"caption":"This is why testing early (and well) saves money."},"davidTip":"When stakeholders ask \"why does testing take so long?\", reframe it. As a test manager I never sell testing as a cost — I sell it as risk reduction. \"We can ship today with this known risk, or spend two hours covering the payment path.\" Give the business the decision in their language: money and risk.","miniChallenge":"Think of a recent news story about a software failure (an outage, a data leak, a billing error). In 4–5 sentences, explain what testing might have caught it and what the failure likely cost the company.","modelAnswer":"## Example\nA bank's app went down during a payday weekend after an untested update. Customers could not access funds, social media filled with complaints, and the regulator asked questions.\n\nA regression test of the login and balance screens on the release candidate would likely have caught it. The cost was not just the fix — it was reputation, customer trust and regulatory scrutiny, which dwarf the price of a few hours of testing.","portfolioBuilder":"Add a short \"Why quality matters\" paragraph to your glossary note. Being able to articulate the business value of testing is exactly what hiring managers probe for."}$ench$::jsonb
from public.modules m join public.courses c on c.id = m.course_id
where l.module_id = m.id and c.slug = '90-day-software-testing-career-roadmap'
  and m.module_number = 1 and l.lesson_number = 2;

update public.lessons l set enhancements = $ench${"industryStory":"A new tester joined a team and could not understand why bugs they raised \"late\" caused friction. The reason: they did not understand the SDLC. The team worked in two-week sprints, and raising a major design flaw on the last day — something that should have surfaced at refinement — meant the work could not ship.\n\nUnderstanding the lifecycle is what lets a tester add value at the right moment.","visualAid":{"type":"timeline","title":"The Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC)","steps":[{"label":"Requirements","detail":"What needs building and why"},{"label":"Design","detail":"How it will be built"},{"label":"Development","detail":"Writing the code"},{"label":"Testing","detail":"Verifying it meets expectations"},{"label":"Deployment","detail":"Releasing to users"},{"label":"Maintenance","detail":"Fixes and improvements"}]},"davidTip":"The single biggest lift a junior tester can make is to get involved earlier in the SDLC. In real QA teams, a tester who asks sharp questions at requirements and design prevents defects that would otherwise cost days later. \"Shift left\" is not jargon — it is where your value compounds.","miniChallenge":"Map a feature you use (e.g. \"add a profile photo\") to the six SDLC stages. Write one line per stage describing what happens and where a tester could contribute.","modelAnswer":"## Example — \"add a profile photo\"\n- Requirements: agree allowed file types and max size — tester asks \"what about a 50MB file or a .exe?\"\n- Design: where the upload lives, error messages — tester reviews for testability\n- Development: the upload is built\n- Testing: valid/invalid files, large files, cancel mid-upload\n- Deployment: released behind a feature flag\n- Maintenance: monitor errors; fix issues users report","portfolioBuilder":"In your portfolio you will eventually include a test plan. Knowing the SDLC lets you explain where your testing fits — reviewers love a candidate who sees the whole lifecycle, not just \"run the tests\".","resourcePreview":{"name":"SDLC Cheat Sheet","purpose":"A one-page summary of the SDLC stages and the tester’s role at each.","whenToUse":"Reference it when planning testing or answering lifecycle interview questions.","formats":["PDF","DOCX"]}}$ench$::jsonb
from public.modules m join public.courses c on c.id = m.course_id
where l.module_id = m.id and c.slug = '90-day-software-testing-career-roadmap'
  and m.module_number = 1 and l.lesson_number = 3;

update public.lessons l set enhancements = $ench${"industryStory":"Two testers were given the same feature. One started clicking immediately; the other spent twenty minutes on test analysis and a quick test plan first. The second tester found more issues, in less time, and could explain exactly what was and was not covered. The difference was following the STLC instead of improvising.","visualAid":{"type":"flow","title":"The Software Testing Life Cycle (STLC)","steps":[{"label":"Requirement Analysis"},{"label":"Test Planning"},{"label":"Test Case Design"},{"label":"Environment Setup"},{"label":"Test Execution"},{"label":"Test Closure"}],"caption":"A repeatable process that turns \"clicking around\" into professional testing."},"davidTip":"Even under pressure, do not skip analysis and design. As a QA lead, when someone tells me \"I tested it\", my next question is \"what did you cover, and what did you decide not to?\" The STLC is what lets you answer that with confidence instead of a shrug.","miniChallenge":"For a login feature, write a mini test plan: 3 things in scope, 2 things out of scope, and 5 test case titles you would design.","modelAnswer":"## Example — Login\n**In scope:** valid login, invalid password, locked account after N attempts.\n**Out of scope:** password-reset emails (separate feature), social login (not built yet).\n**Test case titles:**\n- Valid email and password logs in successfully\n- Wrong password shows a clear error\n- Empty fields are rejected\n- Account locks after 5 failed attempts\n- Email is case-insensitive","portfolioBuilder":"This mini test plan is the seed of a real portfolio artefact. Keep it — you will expand the test-planning skill in later modules and showcase a full plan at the end.","resourcePreview":{"name":"STLC Cheat Sheet","purpose":"The STLC phases with the key activities and outputs of each.","whenToUse":"Use it as a checklist when you start testing any new feature.","formats":["PDF","DOCX"]}}$ench$::jsonb
from public.modules m join public.courses c on c.id = m.course_id
where l.module_id = m.id and c.slug = '90-day-software-testing-career-roadmap'
  and m.module_number = 1 and l.lesson_number = 4;

update public.lessons l set enhancements = $ench${"industryStory":"A candidate told an interviewer they wanted to \"be in QA\" but could not say what kind of role. Another candidate said: \"I want to start as a manual QA analyst, build automation skills toward an SDET role, and grow into a test lead.\" They got the callback — because they understood the landscape and had a direction.","visualAid":{"type":"comparison","title":"Common QA roles and what they focus on","headers":["Role","Focus","Typical work"],"rows":[["Manual / QA Tester","Executing tests","Test cases, exploratory testing, bug reports"],["QA Analyst","Test design & coverage","Test plans, risk-based testing, requirements review"],["Automation / SDET","Automated checks","Building and maintaining test frameworks"],["Test Lead","Coordinating testing","Strategy, estimates, reporting, mentoring"],["QA Manager","People & process","Hiring, quality strategy, stakeholder management"]]},"davidTip":"You do not need to pick a final destination on day one. But in real QA teams, the people who progress fastest know the next rung on the ladder and deliberately build toward it. Pick a direction — manual to analyst, or analyst to SDET — and let it guide what you practise.","miniChallenge":"Write your own 12-month QA direction in 3 sentences: the role you would start in, the one you would aim for next, and two skills you would build to get there.","modelAnswer":"## Example\n\"I would start as a manual QA tester to learn the product and fundamentals. Within a year I would aim to move toward a QA analyst role, owning test design and risk-based coverage. To get there I would build SQL and API testing skills, and start learning automation basics.\"","portfolioBuilder":"This becomes your \"career direction\" line for your CV summary and LinkedIn headline (built in Module 11). Recruiters respond to candidates with a clear, credible direction.","resourcePreview":{"name":"QA Career Roadmap Poster","purpose":"A visual map of QA roles and how testers typically progress between them.","whenToUse":"Use it to choose your direction and plan the skills to build.","formats":["PDF"]}}$ench$::jsonb
from public.modules m join public.courses c on c.id = m.course_id
where l.module_id = m.id and c.slug = '90-day-software-testing-career-roadmap'
  and m.module_number = 1 and l.lesson_number = 5;

update public.lessons l set enhancements = $ench${"industryStory":"A team shipped a feature that \"passed testing\" but fell over the moment 500 users hit it at once. The functional tests all passed — nobody had considered performance. Knowing the *types* of testing is what stops you from declaring something \"tested\" when a whole dimension of risk was never checked.","visualAid":{"type":"comparison","title":"Common types of testing","headers":["Type","What it checks","Example"],"rows":[["Functional","Does it do what it should?","Login works with valid details"],["Regression","Did a change break something?","Re-test checkout after a payment change"],["Smoke","Is the build stable enough to test?","App launches and core pages load"],["Performance","Is it fast and stable under load?","500 users check out at once"],["Usability","Is it easy to use?","A new user can complete sign-up"],["Security","Is it safe?","A user cannot see another’s data"]]},"davidTip":"When you report results, name the type of testing you did — and just as importantly, what you did not do. \"Functional and regression passed; performance and security were not in scope\" is the kind of honest, precise statement that builds trust with a QA lead.","miniChallenge":"For an online banking app, list one realistic test for each of these types: functional, regression, performance, security, and usability.","modelAnswer":"## Example — online banking\n- Functional: a transfer between two accounts moves the correct amount\n- Regression: after a UI update, the balance still displays correctly\n- Performance: the dashboard loads within 2 seconds at peak time\n- Security: a logged-in user cannot view another customer’s statements\n- Usability: a first-time user can set up a payee without help","portfolioBuilder":"Understanding test types lets you write a \"test approach\" section in your portfolio test plan that covers more than just the happy path — a clear signal of maturity to reviewers.","resourcePreview":{"name":"Software Testing Glossary","purpose":"Definitions of the testing types and terms covered in this lesson.","whenToUse":"Revise from it before interviews — testing types are a very common question.","formats":["PDF","DOCX"]}}$ench$::jsonb
from public.modules m join public.courses c on c.id = m.course_id
where l.module_id = m.id and c.slug = '90-day-software-testing-career-roadmap'
  and m.module_number = 1 and l.lesson_number = 6;

update public.lessons l set enhancements = $ench${"davidTip":"Treat knowledge checks as interview rehearsal, not a quiz to rush. For each answer, say it out loud as if explaining to an interviewer. The goal is not to recall the word — it is to explain the idea clearly.","miniChallenge":"Without looking back, write one-sentence answers to: (1) the difference between QA and testing, (2) why bugs cost more later, (3) what the STLC is. Then check yourself against the lessons."}$ench$::jsonb
from public.modules m join public.courses c on c.id = m.course_id
where l.module_id = m.id and c.slug = '90-day-software-testing-career-roadmap'
  and m.module_number = 1 and l.lesson_number = 7;

update public.lessons l set enhancements = $ench${"davidTip":"Treat this first assignment as a portfolio piece, not homework. Structure it clearly, use the right terms, and make it something you would be comfortable showing an interviewer. First impressions of your written work matter.","miniChallenge":"Before writing the full assignment, draft a one-paragraph outline: what you will cover (SDLC, testing types, the QA role) and one real example you will use. A clear outline makes the assignment far easier to write well.","modelAnswer":"## Example outline\n\"I'll explain the six SDLC stages using a simple feature (profile photo upload) as the running example, then describe three testing types I'd apply to it (functional, regression, usability), and finish with how a QA tester adds value at each SDLC stage — especially by getting involved early.\"","managersReview":{"intro":"If I received this assignment as a QA lead, here is what I would look for:","strengths":["Correct use of terms (SDLC, STLC, testing types) in your own words","A concrete example rather than only definitions","Clear, well-structured writing that is easy to follow"],"gaps":["Definitions copied without a supporting example","No mention of where the tester adds value in the lifecycle","Testing described as only \"finding bugs\""],"improvements":["Add one real example per concept","Include a sentence on testing as risk information, not just bug-finding","Proofread — clean, professional writing is part of the assessment"]},"portfolioBuilder":"This assignment is the first item in your QA portfolio. Save your submission — by Module 12 you will have a full set of artefacts, and a strong, well-written first piece sets the tone.","resourcePreview":{"name":"SDLC Cheat Sheet","purpose":"Use it as the reference/structure for the SDLC part of your assignment.","whenToUse":"Open it while drafting so your stages and terminology are accurate.","formats":["PDF","DOCX"]}}$ench$::jsonb
from public.modules m join public.courses c on c.id = m.course_id
where l.module_id = m.id and c.slug = '90-day-software-testing-career-roadmap'
  and m.module_number = 1 and l.lesson_number = 8;

